<td width="100%" class="title"><font face="Verdana,Arial,helvetica,sans-serif" size="4" color="#0d4d9b"><b>16 Pavillions To Highlight Emerging Product Categories At The 2000 International CES</b></font></td>
</tr>
</table>

	
	



	
	<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0">
	
	<tr>
	
		<td width="18"><img src="/Graphics/Interface/Icons/spacer.gif" width=18 height=1 border=0></td>
	
	
		<td>
	




	

	<p>Arlington, VA - Dec, 13 1999
	<BR>
	With 16 specialized pavilions on tap, the 2000 International CES, held January 6-9 in Las Vegas, will spotlight the hottest emerging technologies-from 1394 connectivity and e-commerce to digital radio and infrared data.  With more than 1,500 exhibitors and 90,000 attendees expected, CES is the new home for e-commerce, MP3, digital radio, DSL, infrared data and Digital Hollywood technology, plus other blossoming product areas. <P>
"As CES continues to be the launch pad for the latest in traditional consumer technologies such as audio, video, computers, telephony, mobile electronics, wireless communications and more, we're also bringing new industry advancements to light with several new product pavilions," said Robbi Lycett, CES vice president. "Some of these pavilions work as incubators for emerging companies and their technologies as they test the market's waters.  Others allow attendees to see all the latest innovations in a new product category in one concentrated area.  All of the pavilions, however, offer new profit-making ideas and business opportunities to CES attendees." <P>
At the Sands, stroll through three technology pavilions that transport the car into the digital age.  The Digital Radio Pavilion showcases the latest innovations in satellite and terrestrial-based digital radio from Digital Radio Express, Lucent Technologies, Sirius Satellite Radio, USA Digital Radio and XM Satellite.   <P>
See the most advanced new vehicle navigation, vehicle safety, emergency notification, wireless IT products, obstacle warning systems, global positioning satellite systems and geographic information satellite systems at the Intelligent Transportation Systems (ITS) Pavilion endorsed by ITS America with exhibitors such as Etak, ETL, InfoMove.com, Navigation Technologies, RoyalTek and TravRoute.  The ITS Data Bus (IDB) Pavilion sponsored by the IDB Forum demonstrates the latest in IDB, smart car and car-based computer technology. <P>
Within the South Hall of the Las Vegas Convention Center (LVCC), the 1394 Showcase hosted by the 1394 Trade Association allows attendees to explore new connectivity for digital consumer electronics, computer and peripheral products through the IEEE 1394 standard.   Technology leaders such as Apple, Compaq, Kenwood, Matsushita, Molex, SoftAcoustik, Sony, Texas Instruments and Zayante will show the latest 1394 technology applications. <P>
The North Hall of the LVCC could be nicknamed "Pavilion Central" with 13 pavilions surrounded by the major computer, information technology, telephony, home networking, home theater and personal electronics manufacturers. <P>
Upside's Digital Living Room highlights the convergence of consumer technology, entertainment, computers and the Internet with companies such as 2wire, Apogee, Avio, Echogent, Electronic Home Networks, HomePNA, Hy-Tek, Integra, Intrigo, Liquid Audio, KBA, Netpliance, Neurosmith, Ravisent, Replay, RF Link, Siemens and Telecruz. With companies such as Clear Band, DigiScents, Packet Video and Webstakes, Digital Hollywood focuses on the impact of the entertainment, computer, communications and consumer technology industries in the digital marketplace of the future.  Both Digital Hollywood and Digital Living Room showcase MP3 technology as well, including exhibits from Casady & Greene, Digital Voice Systems, Dream Quest, Hyun Won, I-Jam Multimedia, Lydstrom, MaxTech, Request Multimedia and Ziplabs. <P>
To show companies how to take their businesses online, CES' new E-Commerce Pavilion, sponsored by PC Computing and Yahoo! Internet Life, houses companies such as Assist Corner, Audiocafe.com, CDS Solutions Group, CETRADE.COM, Click Move, Electronics Partner, GetPlugged.com, Infomatec, International Management Consultants Inc., Roxy.com, Tradeout.com and Xpedior. <P>
Within the telephony and networking arena, CES has three new pavilions for 2000.  The Digital Subscriber Line (DSL) Pavilion, hosted by the ADSL Forum, highlights modem technology that transforms ordinary phone lines into high-speed digital lines for ultra-fast Internet access.  With infrared data showing up in several consumer technologies, such as PDAs, printers, desktop adapters, notebooks, wireless phones, cameras and palm devices, CES attendees can see what new applications are being created for this technology at the IrDA (Infrared Data Association) Pavilion.  Endorsed by the Universal Serial Bus Implementers Forum (USB IF), the USB Pavilion showcases the newest products for connecting computers and peripherals. <P>
Another new pavilion for CES, the Timepiece Pavilion, showcases the finest in timepieces and related timepiece products from About Time, Eastern Watch, Europa Wholesale, Favour Light Enterprises, Geneva Timepiece, Juno International, Luxury International, M&T Vision, Pearl International, Teltime Watch, Timestar, Titanium Marketing, Tru-Time Watch and Wani's Enterprises. <P>
The Emerging Technologies Pavilion, the most popular pavilion at CES, is where investors, venture capitalists, retail buyers, industry analysts and engineers flock to see high-growth companies and next-generation technologies.  Exhibitors include Action Orthotics, Alexandria Digital Literature, Applied Magic, Atico International USA, Azuradisc, Battery Busters, Centerpin Technology Inc., Conner Tech, DVDO, Esprit Development Corp., General Computer Technology, Golden Screens Interactive Technology, Granite Microsystems, Hidden Camera Solutions, Landsman Technology, Led Art.com, Mbox Technology, Miracle Beam, Natural Life, Novation Products Inc., Panacom Technology, Patrick Technologies, PC Anything Inc., Pragmatic Communication Systems, PremiseNet, Redirectory Services Inc., Returnme.com, rma buyDirect and Salutation Consortium Inc. <P>
Five other pavilions return to the 2000 CES covering everything from digital imaging, speech technology, antennas, home security and mobile computing.  The Digital Imaging Pavilion, sponsored by PhotoHighway.com, houses digital cameras, video and electronic imaging and manipulation products, switchers, scanners and OCPs, presentation equipment, monitors and printers from Aeon, Antec, California Electronics, Gamla Kodak, Pixera and Wynit. <P>
The Speech Technology Pavilion, sponsored by Speech Technology Magazine, showcases the advances in speech recognition technology, particularly in telephony, computers, automotive systems, Internet services, home automation and video games. See portable speech recognition devices, voice technology applications, DSP chips and desk and wireless phones from Emkay, Sensory, Sycom and Telex. <P>
With Direct Broadcast Satellite (DBS) systems and high-definition televisions (HDTV) making antennas a must, the Antenna Pavilion showcases the newest in sleek, innovative, high-performance indoor and outdoor designs from Aknet Fuze Television, Channel Master, Data World, Interactive Technology, Jasco Products, Satellite Broadcasting & Communications, Terk Technologies and Winegard.  Attendees also can learn about the Consumer Electronics Association's (CEA) Antenna Mapping Program and www.AntennaWeb.org. <P>
At the Home Security Pavilion, attendees can learn about the latest in integrated security systems, identification products, access control systems, intrusion detection devices, perimeter protection systems and CCTV.  See exhibitors such as Artek USA, Clover, Digital Security Controls, ITI, OK Security, Orchid, Seaview, Windmaster and Wooju America. <P>
CEA is a sector of the Electronic Industries Alliance (EIA), the 75-year-old Arlington, Virginia-based trade organization representing all facets of electronics manufacturing.  CEA represents more than 500 U.S. manufacturers of audio, video, accessories, mobile electronics, communication, information technology and multimedia products that are sold through consumer channels. <P>
CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology.  All profits from CES are reinvested into industry services, including technical training and education, product promotion, engineering standards development, market research and governmental and legal affairs support.  As the first major technology event of the new millennium, the 2000 International CES is the launch pad for 21st century technology. <P>
	<BR>&nbsp;<BR>&nbsp;
	

		
